---
import Guide from '../../layouts/Guide.astro';
---
<Guide
  title="Cloud backup and restore for your SAP Logon systems"
  description="Keep a safe copy of your SAP Logon system list in OneDrive, Google Drive or Dropbox — and restore it on any machine in one click. How the cloud backup feature works."
  keywords="SAP Logon cloud backup, backup SAP GUI OneDrive, restore SAP Logon, SAP connections Google Drive Dropbox, SAP Logon backup restore"
  path="/guides/cloud-backup-sap-logon/"
  tag="How-to"
  updated="February 2026"
>
  <p>
    Losing your SAP Logon system list to a wiped or replaced machine is annoying — and
    avoidable. SAP Logon Transfer can push a timestamped copy of your configuration into
    a cloud folder you already sync, so a fresh machine is one click away from having all
    your systems back.
  </p>

  <figure class="g-figure">
    <img src="/cloud-backup.png" alt="Cloud backup and restore window showing a cloud folder and a list of timestamped backups" />
    <figcaption>Back up to any synced folder, and restore a specific point-in-time copy later.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>
    There are no accounts to create and no API keys. The feature simply reads and writes
    inside a folder you choose — typically your <strong>OneDrive</strong>,
    <strong>Google Drive</strong> or <strong>Dropbox</strong> folder. Your normal cloud
    client syncs that folder to the cloud as usual, so your backup rides along with the
    sync you already trust.
  </p>

  <h2>Backing up</h2>
  <div class="g-steps">
    <div class="g-step">
      <div class="g-step-icon">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M12 22s8-4 8-10V5l-8-3-8 3v7c0 6 8 10 8 10z"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="g-step-body">
        <h3>1. Open Cloud backup &amp; restore</h3>
        <p>From the main window, open <strong>Cloud backup &amp; restore</strong>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="g-step">
      <div class="g-step-icon">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 7h5l2 2h11v9a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H3z"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="g-step-body">
        <h3>2. Choose your cloud folder</h3>
        <p>Click <strong>Choose folder</strong> and point it at your OneDrive, Google
        Drive or Dropbox folder. The tool remembers it for next time.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="g-step">
      <div class="g-step-icon">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M12 3v12m0 0l-4-4m4 4l4-4M5 21h14"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="g-step-body">
        <h3>3. Back up now</h3>
        <p>Click <strong>Back up now</strong>. A timestamped file (for example
        <code>SAPLogon_backup_20260706_111756.xml</code>) is written to the folder and
        appears in the list. Your cloud client syncs it automatically.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Restoring on another machine</h2>
  <p>
    On a new or reinstalled machine, install SAP Logon Transfer, open
    <strong>Cloud backup &amp; restore</strong>, and choose the same cloud folder. Your
    previous backups appear in the list with their date and time. Select the one you want
    and click <strong>Restore selected</strong>.
  </p>
  <blockquote>
    Restore imports your systems safely — it doesn't blindly overwrite. Existing systems
    are kept, only what's missing is added, and a backup of the current state is written
    first.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Why timestamps matter</h2>
  <p>
    Each backup keeps its own date and time, so you're not limited to a single "latest"
    copy. If you reorganised your folders last week and want to go back to how things were,
    pick the earlier backup from the list. It's a simple version history for your system
    list.
  </p>

  <h2>No passwords involved</h2>
  <p>
    As everywhere in the tool, only connection details are backed up — servers, routers
    and system IDs. SAP Logon never stores passwords in these files, so your cloud backup
    is safe to keep.
  </p>

  <h2>Related guides</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/guides/backup-sap-gui-settings/">Back up SAP GUI settings before reinstalling Windows</a></li>
    <li><a href="/guides/move-sap-gui-new-machine/">How to move SAP GUI to a new computer</a></li>
  </ul>

